<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-066-247 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 182 695</DOCID><JOURNAL>Byte  Sept 1991 v16 n9 p122(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>True data. (using authentication for data security; includes arelated article on the checksum method of authentication)(tutorial)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wayner, Peter.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Computer-based information is not nearly as secure as popularnotions of it might seem to imply.andP;  A number of methods have beendevised to help authenticate computer-based documents.andP;  Snefru andMD5 are two cryptographically secure variations of the familiarchecksum; both are difficult to invert.andP;  Public-key encryptiontechniques rely on pairs of keys; messages encrypted with thepublic key can only be decrypted by the corresponding private key.andO;Authentication over a network requires special precautions.andP;  Onesystem developed specifically for network authentication is theMassachusetts Institute of Technology's (MIT's) Kerberos system.andO;Kerberos relies on password protection for security.andP;  The serverwhich grants passwords, the Kerberos Ticket Granting Server, iskept physically secure.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Security SystemsEncryptionData security.andO;Feature:   illustrationprogram.andO;Caption:   Snefru program. (program)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>